Question 55 Explain Inheritance in java?

#interviewquestions #interviewtips

ğŸ‘‰ Inheritance in Java is a mechanism in which one object acquires all the properties and behaviors of a parent object. It is an important part of OOPs (Object Oriented programming system).

ğŸ‘‰ The idea behind inheritance in Java is that you can create new classes that are built upon existing classes. 

ğŸ‘‰ When you inherit from an existing class, you can reuse methods and fields of the parent class. Moreover, you can add new methods and fields in your current class also.

ğŸ‘‰ Inheritance represents the IS-A relationship which is also known as a parent-child relationship.

ğŸ‘¨ğŸ’» Why use Java interface?
ğŸ‘‰ It is used to achieve abstraction.
ğŸ‘‰ By interface, we can support the functionality of multiple inheritances.
ğŸ‘‰ It can be used to achieve loose coupling.

ğŸ‘¨ğŸ’» The syntax of Java Inheritance
class Subclass-name extends Superclass-name  
{  
   //methods and fields  
}  

ğŸ‘‰ The extends keyword indicates that you are making a new class that derives from an existing class. The meaning of "extends" is to increase the functionality.

ğŸ‘‰ In the terminology of Java, a class which is inherited is called a parent or superclass, and the new class is called child or subclass.

ğŸ‘¨ğŸ’» Types of inheritance in java
ğŸ‘‰ On the basis of class, there can be five types of inheritance in java: single, multilevel, multiple, hybrid and hierarchical.
ğŸ‘‰ In java programming, multiple and hybrid inheritance is supported through interface only. 

